<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
  <chapter xml:id="ch-translation" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Translating R Code</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        The combination of first-class environments, lexical scoping, and
        metaprogramming gives us a powerful toolkit for translating R code into
        other languages. One fully-fledged example of this idea is
        <c>dbplyr</c>, which powers the database backends for dplyr, allowing
        you to express data manipulation in R and automatically translate it to
        SQL.
      </p>

      <p>
        In this chapter, we'll develop two simple, but useful, domain-specific
        languages (DSL). The first translates R expressions into HTML, and the
        second translates R expressions into mathematical equations in LaTeX.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <section xml:id="sec-html-dsl">
      <title>HTML</title>

      <p>
        HTML (HyperText Markup Language) is the language that underlies the
        web. It's a special case of SGML (Standard Generalised Markup Language),
        and it's similar to XML (eXtensible Markup Language).
      </p>
    </section>

  </chapter>
